message: To get high scores, focus on using the vial to extract from solid ingredients. Both magical solids (like sunstone, dragon scale) and mundane solids (like obsidian, amber, frog leg, dandelion) yield valuable liquid extracts. The most reliable path to 100 points is combining one magical liquid extract with one mundane liquid extract. The filter can be useful for 'bad stuff' like basilisk venom, improving value, but only use it once as repeated filtering can make items 'overcomplicated' without further benefit. Avoid using the vial on gas or simple liquid ingredients, as it often results in botched extractions.

message: To reliably get 100 points: First, use the 'vial' tool on any 'solid, mundane' ingredient (e.g., amber, mushroom, obsidian) to create a 'mundane extract'. Second, use the 'vial' tool on any 'solid, magical' ingredient (e.g., mandrake root, unicorn horn, sunstone) to create a 'magical extract'. Finally, combine these two extracts (the 'mundane extract' and the 'magical extract') for a 100-value item. Filtering 'ink' can also create a 30-value item, but it's not necessary for the maximum score. Avoid using 'vial' on 'gas' or 'liquid' ingredients, and don't re-vial items that already have 'failed extraction' features, as it usually makes them worse.

Filter 'bad' liquids or gases (kraken ink, basilisk venom, volcanic fumes) to create +30 'filtered' liquids. Avoid vialing gases or filtering already good extracts, as this usually decreases value. Combining more than two items can also reduce value.

message: To succeed, focus on vialing *solid* ingredients. Vialing magical solids (like mandrake root or unicorn horn) yields magical liquid extracts, and vialing mundane solids (like rose petal or mushroom) yields mundane liquid extracts. Combine one magical liquid extract with one mundane liquid extract to achieve the maximum score of 100. Avoid vialing liquid or gas ingredients, as this consistently leads to negative-value botched extractions. Filtering botched items also seems to worsen them, so save the filter for other specific 'bad stuff' if you encounter it.
